passages.text: Equity ResearchAugust 28,2025
F2H26 ARR Guide ImplieWe've Reached the Light at the End of the tunnel

F2Q ARR growth of 20.5% yoy beat cons by 30 bps but was at the low end of elevated investor expectations. FY26 rev guide was only raised by $3M at midpoint vs $21M F2Q beat raising questions as partner headwinds persist.Positively, F2H26 incremental ARR was guided to grow "at least" 40% yoy implying 22%+ yoy ARR growth (we expect 1pt of upside remains) which was above cons 20.8%. Accelerating ARR growth + inflecting FY27 FCF keeps us favorable on shares.
**We will be hosting an earnings** **debrief** **at** **8:00AM** **on** **Thurs,** **Aug** **28** **to** **discuss** **CRWD's** **F2Q26** **results.** **Please** **register** **here.**
**Things We** **Liked:**

**FY26** **ARR** **Guided** **Above** **Cons** **Expectations.** 2H26 new business (not accounting for churn) was guided to grow "at least" 40% yoy which implies FY26 ARR growth of 22%+ yoy. This implies at least $5.185B of ARR which is approx $60M above consensus. We believe that CRWDs guidance methodology has not changed and that a pt of upside remains feasible. It's important to note that the Onum acquisition is not embedded in guidance since that the deal has not closed yet. Making this guidance more impressive is the fact that we continue to believe that the $80M of CCP renewals benefits is more of a FY27 phenomena than F2H26 given it does not occur until customers renew their Flex contract.

**F2Q** **ARR** **Beat** **Cons,** **At** **Low** **End** **of** **Elevated** **Investor** **Expectations.** CRWD reported F2Q ARR of ~$4.66B growing 20% yoy (beat cons ~$4.64B) which was at the low end of elevated investor expectations. Incremental ARR was $221M (+2% yoy growth; not accounting for churn). We calculated that net new ARR (accounting for churn) grew 8% yoy in F2Q vs down 1% in F1Q on a 14 pt easier comp. Accelerating new business was driven by the Flex subscription model (reported >1K Flex customers, >100 "re-Flex" customers, and average deal size of >$1MM ending ARR) and increasing multi-module adoption rates in the Falcon platform.
**Things We're** **Watching:** **-**

**FY26** **Revenue** **Raised** **by** **Less** **Than** **F2Q** **Beat.** CRWD reported F2Q total revenue beating the midpoint of the guide by $21M, but only raised its FY26 rev guide by $3M at the midpoint. Mgmt. attributed this in part to impacts of $10-15M quarterly from the CCP related partner programs each of the next 2QS (this was already embedded in guidance & F2Q was at the bottom of this range) as well as more variability from its services revenue. It remains a bit unclear to us exactly why revenue wouldn't benefit more from the uptick in ARR expectations unless CRWD is continuing to discount/incentivize partners which may be a near term rev headwind. Note that management expects these headwinds to abate in F1Q27.

- Endpoint is the area of software (not just security) where we hear more about competitive displacements than any other. CrowdStrike provides state-of-the-art, next-generation endpoint technology with a foundation in its unique graph database and lightweight agent, which leverages artificial intelligence and machine learning. Integrated technologies beyond endpoint will likely make CrowdStrike stickier than traditional endpoint vendors.
Risk/Reward - 12 Month View

- Emerges as one of the leaders in the market for endpoint security, even with increased macro headwinds.- Continues to add modules, which expands the addressable market and continues to strive for broader platform adoption beyond endpoint.- Customers continue to purchase multiple solutions, and the net retention rate stays consistently around \(120\%\) .- \(\) 500\(PT is DCF - derived and implies 21x EV/ CY26E revenue.

- Emerges as the industry standard for endpoint security but also continues to add modules, which expands the addressable market and maintains hypergrowth.- Successful expansion internationally results in outsized growth for years, leading to improvement in operating leverage.- Customers purchase more solutions than expected and the net retention rate stays consistently above \(120\%\) .- \(\) 550\(PT is DCF - derived and implies 23x EV/ CY26E revenue.

- Revenue growth decelerates faster than expected due to increased competition and further macro pressure in the endpoint market.- Needs to make continued investments to remain relevant in the marketplace.- The company has to continue paying commissions on renewals, which decreases future potential operating leverage.- \(\) 350\(PT is DCF - derived and implies 15x EV/ CY26E revenue.

Top Material Issues: (1) Data_ Security. Cybersecurity companies play a crucial role both in taking responsibility for maintaining data security and in ensuring customers have access to the products and services required to achieve data security. We expect to see continued focus on data security with a threat landscape that continues to grow. (2) Employee, Engagement, Diversity & Inclusion. We see company culture as important in a labor market that continues to be defined by a skill shortage. Additionally, given the known underrepresentation of women and minority groups in the software industry today, a focus on building a diverse workforce is cardinal.
Company Target: (1) Goal of being carbon-neutral by 2030.

Q's- 60Mgt: (1) When can we expect more definitive targets on how you aim to reduce your impact on the environment? (2) How has the focus on data security by your customers changed over the past 24 months? (3) What are some of the definitive actions you are taking to diversify your workforce?

- Successful expansion internationally results in outsized growth for years, leading to improvement in operating leverage.- Acceleration of new customer growth and maintaining strong gross retention rates.- Continued successful execution of company's land and expand strategy leads to continued growth in net revenue retention (120%+) and operating leverage.
Software Sector ESG Integration Refresh

F3Q ARR. Management guided incremental ARR to grow high single digit sequentially which implies \(\) 235- 242M\(of incremental new ARR vs cons\) \ \(202\) . If we account for churn this implies NNARR growth of high 40s yoy vs \(+8\%\) in F2Q on a 32 p. er comp. We believe CRWD can beat total ARR guide by approx 40 bps, in line with the last 5% which should ultimately help drive approx \(23\%\) yoy ARR growth in FY26 (vs \(22\%\) currently guided).

FCF Margin Continues to See Lingering Outage Impacts. CRWD reported F2Q FCF margin of \(24\%\) vs cons' \(21\%\) , a 4 pt decline yoy. Mgmt. noted that F2Q was impacted by \(\) 29M\(of outage & strategic plan costs, which if added back would imply a margin of\) 27\% \(1 pt yoy decline). Mgmt. expects F3Q's to be impacted by\) \ \(51M\) in cash costs related to the outage, but for F4Q to exit at a \(27\%\) margin, which eventually expands to \(30\% +\) in FY27. We believe this margin expansion is supported by higher Flex utilization rates, multi- module adoption, & higher growth platform solutions like Next- Gen Identity & Next- Gen SIEM. Cost efficiencies ( \(5\%\) RIF earlier this year) will also help drive FCF margin.

F3Q Rev Guide Missed Street Expectations. F3Q total rev guide missed cons by \(1\%\) . Mgmt noted that F3Q revenue will be impacted by \(\) 10- 15M\(in amortization impact (also for F4Q) given partner incentives resulting from the CCP program. Note that this is in - line with prior expectations making the revenue guidance a bit confusing given the better than expected ARR guidance. We note that this rev impact is more pronounced but is temporary in nature given that the rev impact is amortized faster than a contract's term. Ultimately, we believe faster adoption of modules via partner incentives should benefit long term growth.
Valuation. CRWD shares AH trade at \(17x\) CY26 rev and \(54x\) CY26 FCF. Our PT of \(\) 500\(is based on\) 54x \(Cons FY28 (CY27) FCF.\)

Non- GAAP Op Margin Beat & Raise. CRWD reported F2Q non- GAAP operating margins at \(22\%\) beating cons by 2 pts. Additionally, CRWD raised FY26 non- GAAP operating margin guidance to \(21.4\%\) at the midpoint vs prior guide of \(20.8\%\) . Operating margins benefited from better than expected top line performance and efficiency gains from strategic realignment. Operating expenses as a \(0\%\) of revenue declined \(\sim 370\) bps sequentially, with benefits spread relatively equally across the S&M and R&D line items.
RPO Accelerates QoQ. CRWD reported RPO of \(\) 7.2\(B in F2Q, growing\) 47\% \(yoy vs\) 45\% \(in F1Q. This implies RPO bookings growth of\) 35\% \(yoy vs\) 37\% \(in F1Q.\)

PAM in Progress: CRWD introduced its own PAM solution in F1Q, given increasing customer demands for next generation identity platforms and the opportunity to capitalize on consolidation trends. Management highlighted that many firms using legacy PAM systems (particularly those not fully utilizing competitors vaults/session logging) are currently in the market for new providers. While vaulting and session logging remain critical features to develop, future market share will likely revolve around machine identity and agentic capability development. We view this as a positive as it places CRWD on a more level playing field despite its relatively limited history in the space.

CrowdStrike To Acquire Onum for Falcon Next- Gen SIEM. CRWD announced that it has entered into an agreement to acquire Onum, a data observability startup. CRWD believes that Onum will be integrated into Falcon Nex- Gen SIEM as "both a pipeline and a filter" for data direct to the platform. While CRWD has not disclosed the terms of the deal (which has not yet closed and is not included into the guidance), Fortune reported that CRWD is set to purchase the company for approx. \(\) 290M\$

Emerging ARR Passes \(>\) 1.5B. CRWD announced that its Next- Gen SIEM, Cloud Security, and Identity Protection business combined to reach over \(\) 1.56B\(in ARR, a greater than\) 40\% \(increase yoy and\) 20\% \(sequential step up since FQ425. Implied Total Net New ARR (not accounting for churn) was down\) 3\% \(yoy in F1H26 vs F1H25, but showed material improvement vs the down\) 25\% \(yoy in F2H25. Next - Gen\)

SIEM ARR grew >95% yoy (incremental ARR grew 50% yoy) while Cloud grew 35%+ (incremental ARR was down 1% yoy vs the down 28% yoy in F2H25). Identity Security showed a strong resurgence (recall that it was the most given away product in CCP), with implied incremental ARR increasing 56% yoy in F1H26 (vs down 82% yoy in F2H25). Core ARR (comprised of Endpoint, vulnerability management, and many other modules) saw net new ARR declines of 32% yoy for the past 6 months which was roughly in line with the down 28% in F2H25. Conversely, Emerging was up 27% yoy in the same time period.

**Core Growth.** While the Emerging ARR growth cohorts are clearly impressive, it implies that the rest of the business is only growing 11% yoy which raises some questions on the saturation of endpoint and the durability of those business. We will continue to monitor this going forward. See Chart 2 for a breakdown of the different 6 month segment growth rates by sector.

**Fed Commentary.** Discussion was limited but upbeat regarding future federal buying prospects. While management didn't offer any quantitative insight, they reiterated CRWD's attractive value proposition as the federal government potentially shifts to a private sector like approach. A federal government that is actively focused on consolidating and reducing costs should be a net benefit to a more comprehensive provider that can out compete on total cost of ownership like CRWD. We estimate that Fed buying constitutes HSD of CRWD's ARR. We expect to receive more guidance regarding this landscape during the F3Q report (given it is the Federal year end).

Falcon Flex Milestones. CRWD eclipsed the 1,000 Falcon Flex customer mark, adding more than 220 customers in the quarter. The number of deals with total deal value over \(\) 10M\(doubled yoy, and the average Flex customer account remains above\) \ \(1M\) in ARR. Flex contract utilization exceeded \(75\%\) with Reflexes occurring just five months after initial Flex subscriptions, on average. In one example, CRWD completed a \(\) 10M+\(reflex of a contract with 18 months remaining. Additionally, management's comments implied >50 new Reflex customers in F2Q, which now make up nearly 10% of the Flex customer base. Reflexes are resulting in a \~50% increase to Flex customer ending ARR. We view these developments as a bright spot on CRWD's earnings and expect Flex/Reflex to drive continued momentum.

CrowdStrikeCrowdStrike (CRWD) was founded in 2011 to reinvent security for the cloud era. The company took a fundamentally new approach that leverages the network effect of crowdsourced data applied to modern security through technologies such as artificial intelligence, or AI, cloud computing, and graph databases. With its Falcon platform, it created the first multi- tenant, cloud native, intelligent security solution capable of protecting workloads across on- premise, virtualized, and cloud- based environments running on a variety of endpoints such as laptops, desktops, servers, virtual machines, and Internet of Things, or IoT, devices. CrowdStrike has 2,516 subscription customers worldwide, including 44 of the Fortune 100, 27 of the top 100 global companies and 9 of the top 20 major banks as of January 31, 2019. The company is headquartered in Sunnyvale, California with operations in the UK, Australia, New Zealand/Asia Pacific, and Middle East. CrowdStrike currently has 1,455 employees as of January 31, 2019.
Our \(\) 500\$ price target equates to 21x EV/CY26E rev and is one of the most expensive in our coverage universe. Risks include competition, slower market growth, and delayed profitability.
Our Price Target of \(\) 675\$ is based on a DCF. Key risks include the PC cycle and risks related to revenues and margins as MSFT transitions to the Cloud.

Our \(\) 235\$ price target is based on a DCF (WACC \(10\%\) ; TG \(5\%\) ), which assumes higher growth in the out years and accounts for stock based comp. Downside risks: product sales slow, lower industry growth, incumbent vendors re- engaging.
